# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: computational-electromagnetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The **boundary element method** (**BEM**) is a numerical computational method of solving linear partial differential equations (PDEs) arising in engineering and mathematical modeling.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] It is similar to the more widely used finite element method, in that it breaks down the object of study into a series of points in space and then iteratively applies calculations at the points.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] BEM differs from FEM (and similar methods) in that it allows the values in interior or exterior points to be calculated using a calculation based on the values at a defined limit, often the outer surface of an object or similar boundary.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] This is accomplished by re-formulating the PDEs as integral equations (i.e. in *boundary integral* form).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] This reduces the calculation of the larger volume to calculations based on the solutions at the boundary, which greatly reduces the total amount of calculations that need to be solved.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] For instance, to consider the transmission of sound through a lake, an FEM would require an enormous volume of points to be calculated, whereas BEM can reduce this to a calculation of the conditions on the exterior surface of the emitter.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] BEM is widely used in stress analysis, fluid mechanics, acoustics, and similar fields.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] It is also very common in the study of electromagnetism, especially the performance of radio antennas.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] In this particular case, it is so widely used that it is generally referred to by another term, the method of moments (MoM).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The boundary element method is also well suited for analyzing fracture mechanics and cracks in solids and there are several BEM approaches for crack problems.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] One such approach is to formulate the conditions on the cracks in terms of hypersingular boundary integral equations, see (Ang 2013) and contact mechanics.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The integral equation may be regarded as an exact solution of the governing partial differential equation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The boundary element method attempts to use the given boundary conditions to fit boundary values into the integral equation, rather than values throughout the space defined by a partial differential equation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Once this is done, in the post-processing stage, the integral equation can then be used again to calculate numerically the solution directly at any desired point in the interior of the solution domain.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] BEM is applicable to problems for which Green's functions can be calculated.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] These usually involve fields in linear homogeneous media.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] This places considerable restrictions on the range and generality of problems to which boundary elements can usefully be applied.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Nonlinearities can be included in the formulation, although they will generally introduce volume integrals which then require the volume to be discretised before solution can be attempted, removing one of the most often cited advantages of BEM.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] A useful technique for treating the volume integral without discretising the volume is the dual-reciprocity method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The technique approximates part of the integrand using radial basis functions (local interpolating functions) and converts the volume integral into boundary integral after collocating at selected points distributed throughout the volume domain (including the boundary).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] In the dual-reciprocity BEM, although there is no need to discretize the volume into meshes, unknowns at chosen points inside the solution domain are involved in the linear algebraic equations approximating the problem being considered.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The Green's function elements connecting pairs of source and field patches defined by the mesh form a matrix, which is solved numerically.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Unless the Green's function is well behaved, at least for pairs of patches near each other, the Green's function must be integrated over either or both the source patch and the field patch.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The form of the method in which the integrals over the source and field patches are the same is called "Galerkin's method".
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Galerkin's method is the obvious approach for problems which are symmetrical with respect to exchanging the source and field points.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] In frequency domain electromagnetics, this is assured by electromagnetic reciprocity.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The cost of computation involved in naive Galerkin implementations is typically quite severe.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] One must loop over each pair of elements (so we get n2 interactions) and for each pair of elements we loop through Gauss points in the elements producing a multiplicative factor proportional to the number of Gauss-points squared.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Also, the function evaluations required are typically quite expensive, involving trigonometric/hyperbolic function calls.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Nonetheless, the principal source of the computational cost is this double-loop over elements producing a fully populated matrix.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The Green's functions, or fundamental solutions, are often problematic to integrate as they are based on a solution of the system equations subject to a singularity load (e.g. the electrical field arising from a point charge).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Integrating such singular fields is not easy.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] For simple element geometries (e.g. planar triangles) analytical integration can be used.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] For more general elements, it is possible to design purely numerical schemes that adapt to the singularity, but at great computational cost.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Of course, when source point and target element (where the integration is done) are far-apart, the local gradient surrounding the point need not be quantified exactly and it becomes possible to integrate easily due to the smooth decay of the fundamental solution.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] It is this feature that is typically employed in schemes designed to accelerate boundary element problem calculations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Derivation of closed-form Green's functions is of particular interest in boundary element method, especially in electromagnetics.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Specifically in the analysis of layered media, derivation of spatial-domain Green's function necessitates the inversion of analytically-derivable spectral-domain Green's function through Sommerfeld path integral.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] This integral can not be evaluated analytically and its numerical integration is costly due to its oscillatory and slowly-converging behaviour.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] For a robust analysis, spatial Green's functions are approximated as complex exponentials with methods such as Prony's method or generalized pencil of function, and the integral is evaluated with Sommerfeld identity.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] This method is known as discrete complex image method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] The boundary element method is often more efficient than other methods, including finite elements, in terms of computational resources for problems where there is a small surface/volume ratio.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Conceptually, it works by constructing a "mesh" over the modelled surface.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] However, for many problems boundary element methods are significantly less efficient than volume-discretisation methods (finite element method, finite difference method, finite volume method).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] A good example of application of the boundary element method is efficient calculation of natural frequencies of liquid sloshing in tanks.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Boundary element method is one of the most effective methods for numerical simulation of contact problems, in particular for simulation of adhesive contacts.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Boundary element formulations typically give rise to fully populated matrices.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] This means that the storage requirements and computational time will tend to grow according to the square of the problem size.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] By contrast, finite element matrices are typically banded (elements are only locally connected) and the storage requirements for the system matrices typically grow quite linearly with the problem size.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/boundary-element-method] Compression techniques (e.g. multipole expansions or adaptive cross approximation/hierarchical matrices) can be used to ameliorate these problems, though at the cost of added complexity and with a success-rate that depends heavily on the nature of the problem being solved and the geometry involved.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It typically involves using computer programs to compute approximate solutions to Maxwell's equations to calculate antenna performance, electromagnetic compatibility, radar cross section and electromagnetic wave propagation when not in free space.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] A large subfield is **antenna modeling** computer programs, which calculate the radiation pattern and electrical properties of radio antennas, and are widely used to design antennas for specific applications.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Several real-world electromagnetic problems like electromagnetic scattering, electromagnetic radiation, modeling of waveguides etc., are not analytically calculable, for the multitude of irregular geometries found in actual devices.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Computational numerical techniques can overcome the inability to derive closed form solutions of Maxwell's equations under various constitutive relations of media, and boundary conditions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This makes *computational electromagnetics* (CEM) important to the design, and modeling of antenna, radar, satellite and other communication systems, nanophotonic devices and high speed silicon electronics, medical imaging, cell-phone antenna design, among other applications.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] CEM typically solves the problem of computing the *E* (electric) and *H* (magnetic) fields across the problem domain (e.g., to calculate antenna radiation pattern for an arbitrarily shaped antenna structure).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Also calculating power flow direction (Poynting vector), a waveguide's normal modes, media-generated wave dispersion, and scattering can be computed from the *E* and *H* fields.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] CEM models may or may not assume symmetry, simplifying real world structures to idealized cylinders, spheres, and other regular geometrical objects.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] CEM models extensively make use of symmetry, and solve for reduced dimensionality from 3 spatial dimensions to 2D and even 1D.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] An eigenvalue problem formulation of CEM allows us to calculate steady state normal modes in a structure.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Transient response and impulse field effects are more accurately modeled by CEM in time domain, by FDTD.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Curved geometrical objects are treated more accurately as finite elements FEM, or non-orthogonal grids.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Beam propagation method (BPM) can solve for the power flow in waveguides.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] CEM is application specific, even if different techniques converge to the same field and power distributions in the modeled domain.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The most common numerical approach is to discretize ("mesh") the problem space in terms of grids or regular shapes ("cells"), and solve Maxwell's equations simultaneously across all cells.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Discretization consumes computer memory, and solving the relevant equations takes significant time.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Large-scale CEM problems face memory and CPU limitations, and combating these limitations is an active area of research.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] High performance clustering, vector processing, and/or parallelism is often required to make the computation practical.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Choosing the right technique for solving a problem is important, as choosing the wrong one can either result in incorrect results, or results which take excessively long time to compute.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] However, the name of a technique does not always tell one how it is implemented, especially for commercial tools, which will often have more than one solver.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Davidson gives two tables comparing the FEM, MoM and FDTD techniques in the way they are normally implemented.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] One table is for both open region (radiation and scattering problems) and another table is for guided wave problems.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Maxwell's equations can be formulated as a hyperbolic system of partial differential equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This gives access to powerful techniques for numerical solutions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It is assumed that the waves propagate in the (*x*,*y*)-plane and restrict the direction of the magnetic field to be parallel to the *z*-axis and thus the electric field to be parallel to the (*x*,*y*) plane.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The wave is called a transverse magnetic (TM) wave.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] In this representation, ${\bar {g}}$ is the forcing function, and is in the same space as ${\bar {u}}$ .
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It can be used to express an externally applied field or to describe an optimization constraint.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] ${\bar {g}}$ may also be explicitly defined equal to zero to simplify certain problems, or to find a characteristic solution, which is often the first step in a method to find the particular inhomogeneous solution.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The discrete dipole approximation is a flexible technique for computing scattering and absorption by targets of arbitrary geometry.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The formulation is based on integral form of Maxwell equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The DDA is an approximation of the continuum target by a finite array of polarizable points.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The points acquire dipole moments in response to the local electric field.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The dipoles of course interact with one another via their electric fields, so the DDA is also sometimes referred to as the coupled dipole approximation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The resulting linear system of equations is commonly solved using conjugate gradient iterations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The discretization matrix has symmetries (the integral form of Maxwell equations has form of convolution) enabling fast Fourier transform to multiply matrix times vector during conjugate gradient iterations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The method of moments (MoM) or boundary element method (BEM) is a numerical computational method of solving linear partial differential equations which have been formulated as integral equations (i.e. in *boundary integral* form).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It can be applied in many areas of engineering and science including fluid mechanics, acoustics, electromagnetics, fracture mechanics, and plasticity.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] MoM has become more popular since the 1980s.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Because it requires calculating only boundary values, rather than values throughout the space, it is significantly more efficient in terms of computational resources for problems with a small surface/volume ratio.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Conceptually, it works by constructing a "mesh" over the modeled surface.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] However, for many problems, MoM are significantly computationally less efficient than volume-discretization methods (finite element method, finite difference method, finite volume method).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] By contrast, finite element matrices are typically banded (elements are only locally connected) and the storage requirements for the system matrices typically grow linearly with the problem size.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Compression techniques (*e.g.* multipole expansions or adaptive cross approximation/hierarchical matrices) can be used to ameliorate these problems, though at the cost of added complexity and with a success-rate that depends heavily on the nature and geometry of the problem.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] MoM is applicable to problems for which Green's functions can be calculated.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This places considerable restrictions on the range and generality of problems suitable for boundary elements.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Nonlinearities can be included in the formulation, although they generally introduce volume integrals which require the volume to be discretized before solution, removing an oft-cited advantage of MoM.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The fast multipole method (FMM) is an alternative to MoM or Ewald summation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It is an accurate simulation technique and requires less memory and processor power than MoM.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The FMM was first introduced by Greengard and Rokhlin and is based on the multipole expansion technique.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The first application of the FMM in computational electromagnetics was by Engheta et al.(1992).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The FMM has also applications in computational bioelectromagnetics in the Charge based boundary element fast multipole method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The PWTD algorithm was introduced in 1998 by Ergin, Shanker, and Michielssen.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The partial element equivalent circuit (PEEC) is a 3D full-wave modeling method suitable for combined electromagnetic and circuit analysis.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Unlike MoM, PEEC is a full spectrum method valid from dc to the maximum frequency determined by the meshing.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] In the PEEC method, the integral equation is interpreted as Kirchhoff's voltage law applied to a basic PEEC cell which results in a complete circuit solution for 3D geometries.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The equivalent circuit formulation allows for additional SPICE type circuit elements to be easily included.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Further, the models and the analysis apply to both the time and the frequency domains.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The circuit equations resulting from the PEEC model are easily constructed using a modified loop analysis (MLA) or modified nodal analysis (MNA) formulation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Besides providing a direct current solution, it has several other advantages over a MoM analysis for this class of problems since any type of circuit element can be included in a straightforward way with appropriate matrix stamps.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The PEEC method has recently been extended to include nonorthogonal geometries.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This model extension, which is consistent with the classical orthogonal formulation, includes the Manhattan representation of the geometries in addition to the more general quadrilateral and hexahedral elements.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This helps in keeping the number of unknowns at a minimum and thus reduces computational time for nonorthogonal geometries.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The Cagniard-deHoop method of moments (CdH-MoM) is a 3-D full-wave time-domain integral-equation technique that is formulated via the Lorentz reciprocity theorem.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Since the CdH-MoM heavily relies on the Cagniard-deHoop method, a joint-transform approach originally developed for the analytical analysis of seismic wave propagation in the crustal model of the Earth, this approach is well suited for the TD EM analysis of planarly-layered structures.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The CdH-MoM has been originally applied to time-domain performance studies of cylindrical and planar antennas and, more recently, to the TD EM scattering analysis of transmission lines in the presence of thin sheets and electromagnetic metasurfaces, for example.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Finite-difference frequency-domain (FDFD) provides a rigorous solution to Maxwell’s equations in the frequency-domain using the finite-difference method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] FDFD is arguably the simplest numerical method that still provides a rigorous solution.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It is incredibly versatile and able to solve virtually any problem in electromagnetics.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The primary drawback of FDFD is poor efficiency compared to other methods.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] On modern computers, however, a huge array of problems are easily handled such as calculated guided modes in waveguides, calculating scattering from an object, calculating transmission and reflection from photonic crystals, calculate photonic band diagrams, simulating metamaterials, and much more.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] FDFD may be the best "first" method to learn in computational electromagnetics (CEM).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It involves almost all the concepts encountered with other methods, but in a much simpler framework.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Concepts include boundary conditions, linear algebra, injecting sources, representing devices numerically, and post-processing field data to calculate meaningful things.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This will help a person learn other techniques as well as provide a way to test and benchmark those other techniques.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] FDFD is very similar to finite-difference time-domain (FDTD).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Both methods represent space as an array of points and enforces Maxwell’s equations at each point.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] FDFD puts this large set of equations into a matrix and solves all the equations simultaneously using linear algebra techniques.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] In contrast, FDTD continually iterates over these equations to evolve a solution over time.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Numerically, FDFD and FDTD are very similar, but their implementations are very different.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Finite-difference time-domain (FDTD) is a popular CEM technique.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It has an exceptionally simple implementation for a full wave solver.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It is at least an order of magnitude less work to implement a basic FDTD solver than either an FEM or MoM solver.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] FDTD is the only technique where one person can realistically implement oneself in a reasonable time frame, but even then, this will be for a quite specific problem.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Since it is a time-domain method, solutions can cover a wide frequency range with a single simulation run, provided the time step is small enough to satisfy the Nyquist–Shannon sampling theorem for the desired highest frequency.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] FDTD belongs in the general class of grid-based differential time-domain numerical modeling methods.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Maxwell's equations (in partial differential form) are modified to central-difference equations, discretized, and implemented in software.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The equations are solved in a cyclic manner: the electric field is solved at a given instant in time, then the magnetic field is solved at the next instant in time, and the process is repeated over and over again.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The basic FDTD algorithm traces back to a seminal 1966 paper by Kane Yee in IEEE Transactions on Antennas and Propagation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Allen Taflove originated the descriptor "Finite-difference time-domain" and its corresponding "FDTD" acronym in a 1980 paper in IEEE Trans.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Since about 1990, FDTD techniques have emerged as the primary means to model many scientific and engineering problems addressing electromagnetic wave interactions with material structures.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] An effective technique based on a time-domain finite-volume discretization procedure was introduced by Mohammadian et al. in 1991.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Approximately 30 commercial and university-developed software suites are available.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Among many time domain methods, discontinuous Galerkin time domain (DGTD) method has become popular recently since it integrates advantages of both the finite volume time domain (FVTD) method and the finite element time domain (FETD) method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Like FVTD, the numerical flux is used to exchange information between neighboring elements, thus all operations of DGTD are local and easily parallelizable.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Similar to FETD, DGTD employs unstructured mesh and is capable of high-order accuracy if the high-order hierarchical basis function is adopted.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] With the above merits, DGTD method is widely implemented for the transient analysis of multiscale problems involving large number of unknowns.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] MRTD is an adaptive alternative to the finite difference time domain method (FDTD) based on wavelet analysis.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The finite element method (FEM) is used to find approximate solution of partial differential equations (PDE) and integral equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The solution approach is based either on eliminating the time derivatives completely (steady state problems), or rendering the PDE into an equivalent ordinary differential equation, which is then solved using standard techniques such as finite differences, etc.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] There are many ways of doing this, with various advantages and disadvantages.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The finite element method is a good choice for solving partial differential equations over complex domains or when the desired precision varies over the entire domain.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The finite integration technique (FIT) is a spatial discretization scheme to numerically solve electromagnetic field problems in time and frequency domain.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It preserves basic topological properties of the continuous equations such as conservation of charge and energy.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] FIT was proposed in 1977 by Thomas Weiland and has been enhanced continually over the years.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This method covers the full range of electromagnetics (from static up to high frequency) and optic applications and is the basis for commercial simulation tools: CST Studio Suite developed by Computer Simulation Technology (CST AG) and Electromagnetic Simulation solutions developed by Nimbic.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The basic idea of this approach is to apply the Maxwell equations in integral form to a set of staggered grids.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This method stands out due to high flexibility in geometric modeling and boundary handling as well as incorporation of arbitrary material distributions and material properties such as anisotropy, non-linearity and dispersion.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Furthermore, the use of a consistent dual orthogonal grid (e.g.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Cartesian grid) in conjunction with an explicit time integration scheme (e.g. leap-frog-scheme) leads to compute and memory-efficient algorithms, which are especially adapted for transient field analysis in radio frequency (RF) applications.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This class of marching-in-time computational techniques for Maxwell's equations uses either discrete Fourier or discrete Chebyshev transforms to calculate the spatial derivatives of the electric and magnetic field vector components that are arranged in either a 2-D grid or 3-D lattice of unit cells.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] PSTD causes negligible numerical phase velocity anisotropy errors relative to FDTD, and therefore allows problems of much greater electrical size to be modeled.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] PSSD solves Maxwell's equations by propagating them forward in a chosen spatial direction.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The fields are therefore held as a function of time, and (possibly) any transverse spatial dimensions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The method is pseudo-spectral because temporal derivatives are calculated in the frequency domain with the aid of FFTs.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Because the fields are held as functions of time, this enables arbitrary dispersion in the propagation medium to be rapidly and accurately modelled with minimal effort.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] However, the choice to propagate forward in space (rather than in time) brings with it some subtleties, particularly if reflections are important.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Transmission line matrix (TLM) can be formulated in several means as a direct set of lumped elements solvable directly by a circuit solver (ala SPICE, HSPICE, et al.), as a custom network of elements or via a scattering matrix approach.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] TLM is a very flexible analysis strategy akin to FDTD in capabilities, though more codes tend to be available with FDTD engines.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] In this method, in two-dimensional case, Maxwell equations are computed in two steps, whereas in three-dimensional case Maxwell equations are divided into three spatial coordinate directions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Stability and dispersion analysis of the three-dimensional LOD-FDTD method have been discussed in detail.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Eigenmode expansion (EME) is a rigorous bi-directional technique to simulate electromagnetic propagation which relies on the decomposition of the electromagnetic fields into a basis set of local eigenmodes.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The eigenmodes are found by solving Maxwell's equations in each local cross-section.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Eigenmode expansion can solve Maxwell's equations in 2D and 3D and can provide a fully vectorial solution provided that the mode solvers are vectorial.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It offers very strong benefits compared with the FDTD method for the modelling of optical waveguides, and it is a popular tool for the modelling of fiber optics and silicon photonics devices.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Physical optics (PO) is the name of a high frequency approximation (short-wavelength approximation) commonly used in optics, electrical engineering and applied physics.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] It is an intermediate method between geometric optics, which ignores wave effects, and full wave electromagnetism, which is a precise theory.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The word "physical" means that it is more physical than geometrical optics and not that it is an exact physical theory.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The approximation consists of using ray optics to estimate the field on a surface and then integrating that field over the surface to calculate the transmitted or scattered field.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] This resembles the Born approximation, in that the details of the problem are treated as a perturbation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The uniform theory of diffraction (UTD) is a high frequency method for solving electromagnetic scattering problems from electrically small discontinuities or discontinuities in more than one dimension at the same point.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The uniform theory of diffraction approximates near field electromagnetic fields as quasi optical and uses ray diffraction to determine diffraction coefficients for each diffracting object-source combination.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] These coefficients are then used to calculate the field strength and phase for each direction away from the diffracting point.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] These fields are then added to the incident fields and reflected fields to obtain a total solution.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Validation is one of the key issues facing electromagnetic simulation users.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The user must understand and master the validity domain of its simulation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Answering this question involves three steps: comparison between simulation results and analytical formulation, cross-comparison between codes, and comparison of simulation results with measurement.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] For example, assessing the value of the radar cross section of a plate with the analytical formula: ${\text{RCS}}_{\text{Plate}}={\frac {4\pi A^{2}}{\lambda ^{2}}},$ where **A** is the surface of the plate and $\lambda$ is the wavelength.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The next curve presenting the RCS of a plate computed at 35 GHz can be used as reference example.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] One example is the cross comparison of results from method of moments and asymptotic methods in their validity domains.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The final validation step is made by comparison between measurements and simulation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] For example, the RCS calculation and the measurement of a complex metallic object at 35 GHz.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] The computation implements GO, PO and PTD for the edges.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Validation processes can clearly reveal that some differences can be explained by the differences between the experimental setup and its reproduction in the simulation environment.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] There are now many efficient codes for solving electromagnetic scattering problems.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/computational-electromagnetics] Solutions which are analytical, such as Mie solution for scattering by spheres or cylinders, can be used to validate more involved techniques.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The term "Maxwell's equations" is often also used for equivalent alternative formulations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Versions of Maxwell's equations based on the electric and magnetic scalar potentials are preferred for explicitly solving the equations as a boundary value problem, analytical mechanics, or for use in quantum mechanics.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The covariant formulation (on spacetime rather than space and time separately) makes the compatibility of Maxwell's equations with special relativity manifest.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations in curved spacetime, commonly used in high-energy and gravitational physics, are compatible with general relativity.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations are named after the physicist and mathematician James Clerk Maxwell, who, in 1861 and 1862, published an early form of the equations that included the Lorentz force law.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The publication of the equations marked the unification of a theory for previously separately described phenomena: magnetism, electricity, light, and associated radiation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The modern form of the equations in their most common formulation is credited to Oliver Heaviside.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Since the mid-20th century, it has been understood that Maxwell's equations do not give an exact description of electromagnetic phenomena, but are instead a classical limit of the more precise theory of quantum electrodynamics.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The two most commonly used variants of Maxwell's equations are the *microscopic* and *macroscopic* differential form.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The coefficient of the proportion is the permittivity of free space.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Gauss's law for magnetism states that electric charges have no magnetic analogues, called magnetic monopoles; no north or south magnetic poles exist in isolation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Instead, the magnetic field of a material is attributed to a dipole, and the net outflow of the magnetic field through a closed surface is zero.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Magnetic dipoles may be represented as loops of current or inseparable pairs of equal and opposite "magnetic charges".
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Precisely, the total magnetic flux through a Gaussian surface is zero, and the magnetic field is a solenoidal vector field.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The Maxwell–Faraday version of Faraday's law of induction describes how a time-varying magnetic field corresponds to the negative curl of an electric field.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In integral form, it states that the work per unit charge required to move a charge around a closed loop equals the rate of change of the magnetic flux through the enclosed surface.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The electromagnetic induction is the operating principle behind many electric generators: for example, a rotating bar magnet creates a changing magnetic field and generates an electric field in a nearby wire.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The original law of Ampère states that magnetic fields relate to electric current.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's addition states that magnetic fields also relate to changing electric fields, which Maxwell called displacement current.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The integral form states that electric and displacement currents are associated with a proportional magnetic field along any enclosing curve.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's modification of Ampère's circuital law is important because the laws of Ampère and Gauss must otherwise be adjusted for static fields.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] As a consequence, it predicts that a rotating magnetic field occurs with a changing electric field.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] A further consequence is the existence of self-sustaining electromagnetic waves which travel through empty space.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The speed calculated for electromagnetic waves, which could be predicted from experiments on charges and currents, matches the speed of light; indeed, light *is* one form of electromagnetic radiation (as are X-rays, radio waves, and others).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell understood the connection between electromagnetic waves and light in 1861, thereby unifying the theories of electromagnetism and optics.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In the electric and magnetic field formulation there are four equations that determine the fields for given charge and current distribution.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] A separate law of nature, the Lorentz force law, describes how the electric and magnetic fields act on charged particles and currents.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] By convention, a version of this law in the original equations by Maxwell is no longer included.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The vector calculus formalism below, the work of Oliver Heaviside, has become standard.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] It is rotationally invariant, and therefore mathematically more transparent than Maxwell's original 20 equations in *x*, *y* and *z* components.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The relativistic formulations are more symmetric and Lorentz invariant.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For the same equations expressed using tensor calculus or differential forms (see *§ Alternative formulations*).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The differential and integral formulations are mathematically equivalent; both are useful.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The integral formulation relates fields within a region of space to fields on the boundary and can often be used to simplify and directly calculate fields from symmetric distributions of charges and currents.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] On the other hand, the differential equations are purely *local* and are a more natural starting point for calculating the fields in more complicated (less symmetric) situations, for example using finite element analysis.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Symbols in **bold** represent vector quantities, and symbols in *italics* represent scalar quantities, unless otherwise indicated.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The equations introduce the electric field, **E**, a vector field, and the magnetic field, **B**, a pseudovector field, each generally having a time and location dependence.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The equations are a little easier to interpret with time-independent surfaces and volumes.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Time-independent surfaces and volumes are "fixed" and do not change over a given time interval.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The definitions of charge, electric field, and magnetic field can be altered to simplify theoretical calculation, by absorbing dimensioned factors of *ε*0 and *μ*0 into the units (and thus redefining these).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] With a corresponding change in the values of the quantities for the Lorentz force law this yields the same physics, i.e. trajectories of charged particles, or work done by an electric motor.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Such modified definitions are conventionally used with the Gaussian (CGS) units.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The equations simplify slightly when a system of quantities is chosen in the speed of light, *c*, is used for nondimensionalization, so that, for example, seconds and lightseconds are interchangeable, and *c* = 1.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Further changes are possible by absorbing factors of 4*π*.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This process, called rationalization, affects whether Coulomb's law or Gauss's law includes such a factor (see *Heaviside–Lorentz units*, used mainly in particle physics).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The equivalence of the differential and integral formulations are a consequence of the Gauss divergence theorem and the Kelvin–Stokes theorem.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This is the differential equations formulation of Gauss equation up to a trivial rearrangement.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] which is satisfied for all Ω if and only if $\nabla \cdot \mathbf {B} =0$ everywhere.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The equivalence of Faraday's law in differential and integral form follows likewise.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The line integrals and curls are analogous to quantities in classical fluid dynamics: the circulation of a fluid is the line integral of the fluid's flow velocity field around a closed loop, and the vorticity of the fluid is the curl of the velocity field.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The invariance of charge can be derived as a corollary of Maxwell's equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The left-hand side of the Ampère–Maxwell law has zero divergence by the div–curl identity.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In particular, in an isolated system the total charge is conserved.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The quantity $\mu _{0}\varepsilon _{0}$ has the dimension (T/L)2.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Already during Maxwell's lifetime, it was found that the known values for $\varepsilon _{0}$ and $\mu _{0}$ give $c\approx 2.998\times 10^{8}~{\text{m/s}}$ , then already known to be the speed of light in free space.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This led him to propose that light and radio waves were propagating electromagnetic waves, since amply confirmed.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In the new SI system, only *c* keeps its defined value, and the electron charge gets a defined value.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In materials with relative permittivity, *ε*r, and relative permeability, *μ*r, the phase velocity of light becomes $v_{\text{p}}={\frac {1}{\sqrt {\mu _{0}\mu _{\text{r}}\varepsilon _{0}\varepsilon _{\text{r}}}}},$ which is usually less than *c*.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In addition, **E** and **B** are perpendicular to each other and to the direction of wave propagation, and are in phase with each other.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] A sinusoidal plane wave is one special solution of these equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations explain how these waves can physically propagate through space.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The changing magnetic field creates a changing electric field through Faraday's law.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In turn, that electric field creates a changing magnetic field through Maxwell's modification of Ampère's circuital law.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This perpetual cycle allows these waves, now known as electromagnetic radiation, to move through space at velocity *c*.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The above equations are the microscopic version of Maxwell's equations, expressing the electric and the magnetic fields in terms of the (possibly atomic-level) charges and currents present.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This is sometimes called the "general" form, but the macroscopic version below is equally general, the difference being one of bookkeeping.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The microscopic version is sometimes called "Maxwell's equations in vacuum": this refers to the fact that the material medium is not built into the structure of the equations, but appears only in the charge and current terms.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The microscopic version was introduced by Lorentz, who tried to use it to derive the macroscopic properties of bulk matter from its microscopic constituents.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] "Maxwell's macroscopic equations", also known as **Maxwell's equations in matter**, are more similar to those that Maxwell introduced himself.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In the macroscopic equations, the influence of bound charge *Q*b and bound current *I*b is incorporated into the displacement field **D** and the magnetizing field **H**, while the equations depend only on the free charges *Q*f and free currents *I*f.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The cost of this splitting is that the additional fields **D** and **H** need to be determined through phenomenological constituent equations relating these fields to the electric field **E** and the magnetic field **B**, together with the bound charge and current.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] See below for a detailed description of the differences between the microscopic equations, dealing with *total* charge and current including material contributions, useful in air/vacuum; and the macroscopic equations, dealing with *free* charge and current, practical to use within materials.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] When an electric field is applied to a dielectric material its molecules respond by forming microscopic electric dipoles – their atomic nuclei move a tiny distance in the direction of the field, while their electrons move a tiny distance in the opposite direction.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This produces a *macroscopic* *bound charge* in the material even though all of the charges involved are bound to individual molecules.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For example, if every molecule responds the same, similar to that shown in the figure, these tiny movements of charge combine to produce a layer of positive bound charge on one side of the material and a layer of negative charge on the other side.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The bound charge is most conveniently described in terms of the polarization **P** of the material, its dipole moment per unit volume.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] If **P** is uniform, a macroscopic separation of charge is produced only at the surfaces where **P** enters and leaves the material.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For non-uniform **P**, a charge is also produced in the bulk.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Somewhat similarly, in all materials the constituent atoms exhibit magnetic moments that are intrinsically linked to the angular momentum of the components of the atoms, most notably their electrons.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The connection to angular momentum suggests the picture of an assembly of microscopic current loops.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Outside the material, an assembly of such microscopic current loops is not different from a macroscopic current circulating around the material's surface, despite the fact that no individual charge is traveling a large distance.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] These *bound currents* can be described using the magnetization **M**.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] As such, *Maxwell's macroscopic equations* ignore many details on a fine scale that can be unimportant to understanding matters on a gross scale by calculating fields that are averaged over some suitable volume.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In order to apply 'Maxwell's macroscopic equations', it is necessary to specify the relations between displacement field **D** and the electric field **E**, as well as the magnetizing field **H** and the magnetic field **B**.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Equivalently, we have to specify the dependence of the polarization **P** (hence the bound charge) and the magnetization **M** (hence the bound current) on the applied electric and magnetic field.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The equations specifying this response are called constitutive relations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For real-world materials, the constitutive relations are rarely simple, except approximately, and usually determined by experiment.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] See the main article on constitutive relations for a fuller description.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For materials without polarization and magnetization, the constitutive relations are (by definition) $\mathbf {D} =\varepsilon _{0}\mathbf {E} ,\quad \mathbf {H} ={\frac {1}{\mu _{0}}}\mathbf {B} ,$ where *ε*0 is the permittivity of free space and *μ*0 the permeability of free space.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Since there is no bound charge, the total and the free charge and current are equal.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] An alternative viewpoint on the microscopic equations is that they are the macroscopic equations *together* with the statement that vacuum behaves like a perfect linear "material" without additional polarization and magnetization.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] More generally, for linear materials the constitutive relations are $\mathbf {D} =\varepsilon \mathbf {E} ,\quad \mathbf {H} ={\frac {1}{\mu }}\mathbf {B} ,$ where *ε* is the permittivity and *μ* the permeability of the material.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For the magnetizing field $\mathbf {H}$ , however, the linear approximation can break down in common materials like iron leading to phenomena like hysteresis.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Even the linear case can have various complications, however.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Even more generally, in the case of non-linear materials (see for example nonlinear optics), **D** and **P** are not necessarily proportional to **E**, similarly **H** or **M** is not necessarily proportional to **B**.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In general **D** and **H** depend on both **E** and **B**, on location and time, and possibly other physical quantities.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In applications one also has to describe how the free currents and charge density behave in terms of **E** and **B** possibly coupled to other physical quantities like pressure, and the mass, number density, and velocity of charge-carrying particles.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Following are some of the several other mathematical formalisms of Maxwell's equations, with the columns separating the two homogeneous Maxwell equations from the two inhomogeneous ones.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Each formulation has versions directly in terms of the electric and magnetic fields, and indirectly in terms of the electrical potential *φ* and the vector potential **A**.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Potentials were introduced as a convenient way to solve the homogeneous equations, but it was thought that all observable physics was contained in the electric and magnetic fields (or relativistically, the Faraday tensor).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The potentials play a central role in quantum mechanics, however, and act quantum mechanically with observable consequences even when the electric and magnetic fields vanish (Aharonov–Bohm effect).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] See the main article for details of each formulation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The direct spacetime formulations make manifest that the Maxwell equations are relativistically invariant, where space and time are treated on equal footing.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Because of this symmetry, the electric and magnetic fields are treated on equal footing and are recognized as components of the Faraday tensor.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This reduces the four Maxwell equations to two, which simplifies the equations, although we can no longer use the familiar vector formulation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell equations in formulation that do not treat space and time manifestly on the same footing have Lorentz invariance as a hidden symmetry.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This was a major source of inspiration for the development of relativity theory.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Indeed, even the formulation that treats space and time separately is not a non-relativistic approximation and describes the same physics by simply renaming variables.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For this reason the relativistic invariant equations are usually called the Maxwell equations as well.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Each table below describes one formalism.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Other formalisms include the geometric algebra formulation and a matrix representation of Maxwell's equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Historically, a quaternionic formulation was used.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations are partial differential equations that relate the electric and magnetic fields to each other and to the electric charges and currents.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Often, the charges and currents are themselves dependent on the electric and magnetic fields via the Lorentz force equation and the constitutive relations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] These all form a set of coupled partial differential equations which are often very difficult to solve: the solutions encompass all the diverse phenomena of classical electromagnetism.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] As for any differential equation, boundary conditions and initial conditions are necessary for a unique solution.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For example, even with no charges and no currents anywhere in spacetime, there are the obvious solutions for which **E** and **B** are zero or constant, but there are also non-trivial solutions corresponding to electromagnetic waves.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] In some cases, Maxwell's equations are solved over the whole of space, and boundary conditions are given as asymptotic limits at infinity.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Jefimenko's equations (or the closely related Liénard–Wiechert potentials) are the explicit solution to Maxwell's equations for the electric and magnetic fields created by any given distribution of charges and currents.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] It assumes specific initial conditions to obtain the so-called "retarded solution", where the only fields present are the ones created by the charges.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] However, Jefimenko's equations are unhelpful in situations when the charges and currents are themselves affected by the fields they create.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Numerical methods for differential equations can be used to compute approximate solutions of Maxwell's equations when exact solutions are impossible.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] These include the finite element method and finite-difference time-domain method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For more details, see Computational electromagnetics.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations *seem* overdetermined, in that they involve six unknowns (the three components of **E** and **B**) but eight equations (one for each of the two Gauss's laws, three vector components each for Faraday's and Ampère's circuital laws).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This explanation was first introduced by Julius Adams Stratton in 1941.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Although it is possible to simply ignore the two Gauss's laws in a numerical algorithm (apart from the initial conditions), the imperfect precision of the calculations can lead to ever-increasing violations of those laws.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] By introducing dummy variables characterizing these violations, the four equations become not overdetermined after all.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The resulting formulation can lead to more accurate algorithms that take all four laws into account.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Both identities $\nabla \cdot \nabla \times \mathbf {B} \equiv 0,\nabla \cdot \nabla \times \mathbf {E} \equiv 0$ , which reduce eight equations to six independent ones, are the true reason of overdetermination.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Equivalently, the overdetermination can be viewed as implying conservation of electric and magnetic charge, as they are required in the derivation described above but implied by the two Gauss's laws.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] For linear algebraic equations, one can make 'nice' rules to rewrite the equations and unknowns.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The equations can be linearly dependent.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] But in differential equations, and especially partial differential equations (PDEs), one needs appropriate boundary conditions, which depend in not so obvious ways on the equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Even more, if one rewrites them in terms of vector and scalar potential, then the equations are underdetermined because of gauge fixing.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations and the Lorentz force law (along with the rest of classical electromagnetism) are extraordinarily successful at explaining and predicting a variety of phenomena.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] However, they do not account for quantum effects, and so their domain of applicability is limited.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations are thought of as the classical limit of quantum electrodynamics (QED).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Some observed electromagnetic phenomena cannot be explained with Maxwell's equations if the source of the electromagnetic fields are the classical distributions of charge and current.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] These include photon–photon scattering and many other phenomena related to photons or virtual photons, "nonclassical light" and quantum entanglement of electromagnetic fields (see *Quantum optics*).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] E.g. quantum cryptography cannot be described by Maxwell theory, not even approximately.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] The approximate nature of Maxwell's equations becomes more and more apparent when going into the extremely strong field regime (see *Euler–Heisenberg Lagrangian*) or to extremely small distances.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Finally, Maxwell's equations cannot explain any phenomenon involving individual photons interacting with quantum matter, such as the photoelectric effect, Planck's law, the Duane–Hunt law, and single-photon light detectors.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] However, many such phenomena may be explained using a halfway theory of quantum matter coupled to a classical electromagnetic field, either as external field or with the expected value of the charge current and density on the right hand side of Maxwell's equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] This is known as semiclassical theory or self-field QED and was initially discovered by de Broglie and Schrödinger and later fully developed by E.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Popular variations on the Maxwell equations as a classical theory of electromagnetic fields are relatively scarce because the standard equations have stood the test of time remarkably well.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Maxwell's equations posit that there is electric charge, but no magnetic charge (also called magnetic monopoles), in the universe.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] Indeed, magnetic charge has never been observed, despite extensive searches, and may not exist.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/maxwell-s-equations] If they did exist, both Gauss's law for magnetism and Faraday's law would need to be modified, and the resulting four equations would be fully symmetric under the interchange of electric and magnetic fields.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The **method of moments** (**MoM**), also known as the **moment method** and **method of weighted residuals**, is a numerical method in computational electromagnetics.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] It is used in computer programs that simulate the interaction of electromagnetic fields such as radio waves with matter, for example antenna simulation programs like NEC that calculate the radiation pattern of an antenna.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Generally being a frequency-domain method, it involves the projection of an integral equation into a system of linear equations by the application of appropriate boundary conditions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] This is done by using discrete meshes as in finite difference and finite element methods, often for the surface.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The solutions are represented with the linear combination of pre-defined basis functions; generally, the coefficients of these basis functions are the sought unknowns.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Green's functions and Galerkin method play a central role in the method of moments.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] For many applications, the method of moments is identical to the boundary element method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] It is one of the most common methods in microwave and antenna engineering.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Development of boundary element method and other similar methods for different engineering applications is associated with the advent of digital computing in the 1960s.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Prior to this, variational methods were applied to engineering problems at microwave frequencies by the time of World War II.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] While Julian Schwinger and Nathan Marcuvitz have respectively compiled these works into lecture notes and textbooks, Victor Rumsey has formulated these methods into the "reaction concept" in 1954.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The concept was later shown to be equivalent to the Galerkin method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] In the late 1950s, an early version of the method of moments was introduced by Yuen Lo at a course on mathematical methods in electromagnetic theory at University of Illinois.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] In the 1960s, early research work on the method was published by Kenneth Mei, Jean van Bladel and Jack Richmond.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] In the same decade, the systematic theory for the method of moments in electromagnetics was largely formalized by Roger Harrington.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] While the term "the method of moments" was coined earlier by Leonid Kantorovich and Gleb Akilov for analogous numerical applications, Harrington has adapted the term for the electromagnetic formulation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Harrington published the seminal textbook *Field Computation by Moment Methods* on the moment method in 1968.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The development of the method and its indications in radar and antenna engineering attracted interest; MoM research was subsequently supported by the United States government.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The method was further popularized by the introduction of generalized antenna modeling codes such as Numerical Electromagnetics Code, which was released into public domain by the United States government in the late 1980s.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] In the 1990s, introduction of fast multipole and multilevel fast multipole methods enabled efficient MoM solutions to problems with millions of unknowns.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Being one of the most common simulation techniques in RF and microwave engineering, the method of moments forms the basis of many commercial design software such as FEKO.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Many non-commercial and public domain codes of different sophistications are also available.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] In addition to its use in electrical engineering, the method of moments has been applied to light scattering and plasmonic problems.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] An inhomogeneous integral equation can be expressed as: $L(f)=g$ where *L* denotes a linear operator, *g* denotes the known forcing function and *f* denotes the unknown function.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The aim of the method of moments is to minimize this residual, which can be done by using appropriate weighting or testing functions, hence the name method of weighted residuals.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The resulting matrix is often referred to as the impedance matrix.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The coefficients of the basis functions can be obtained through inverting the matrix.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] For large matrices with a large number of unknowns, iterative methods such as conjugate gradient method can be used for acceleration.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The actual field distributions can be obtained from the coefficients and the associated integrals.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The interactions between each basis function in MoM is ensured by Green's function of the system.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Different basis functions can be chosen to model the expected behavior of the unknown function in the domain; these functions can either be subsectional or global.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Choice of Dirac delta function as basis function is known as point-matching or collocation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] This corresponds to enforcing the boundary conditions on N discrete points and is often used to obtain approximate solutions when the inner product operation is cumbersome to perform.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Other subsectional basis functions include pulse, piecewise triangular, piecewise sinusoidal and rooftop functions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Glisson in 1982, are known as RWG basis functions and are widely used in MoM.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Characteristic basis functions were also introduced to accelerate computation and reduce the matrix equation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The testing and basis functions are often chosen to be the same; this is known as the Galerkin method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Depending on the application and studied structure, the testing and basis functions should be chosen appropriately to ensure convergence and accuracy, as well as to prevent possible high order algebraic singularities.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Depending on the application and sought variables, different integral or integro-differential equations are used in MoM.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Radiation and scattering by thin wire structures, such as many types of antennas, can be modeled by specialized equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] For surface problems, common integral equation formulations include electric field integral equation (EFIE), magnetic field integral equation (MFIE) and mixed-potential integral equation (MPIE).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] As many antenna structures can be approximated as wires, thin wire equations are of interest in MoM applications.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Two commonly used thin-wire equations are Pocklington and Hallén integro-differential equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Pocklington's equation precedes the computational techniques, having been introduced in 1897 by Henry Cabourn Pocklington.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The equation can be generalized to different excitation schemes, including magnetic frills.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Hallén integral equation, published by E.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] This equation, despite being more well-behaved than the Pocklington's equation, is generally restricted to the delta-gap voltage excitations at the antenna feed point, which can be represented as an impressed electric field.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The boundary conditions are met at a defined PEC surface.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] EFIE is a Fredholm integral equation of the first kind.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] MFIE is often formulated to be a Fredholm integral equation of the second kind and is generally well-posed.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Nevertheless, the formulation necessitates the use of closed surfaces, which limits its applications.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Many different surface and volume integral formulations for MoM exist.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] In many cases, EFIEs are converted to mixed potential integral equations (MFIE) through the use of Lorenz gauge condition; this aims to reduce the orders of singularities through the use of magnetic vector and scalar electric potentials.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] In order to bypass the internal resonance problem in dielectric scattering calculations, combined-field integral equation (CFIE) and Poggio—Miller—Chang—Harrington—Wu—Tsai (PMCHWT) formulations are also used.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Another approach, the volumetric integral equation, necessitates the discretization of the volume elements and is often computationally expensive.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] MoM can also be integrated with physical optics theory and finite element method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Appropriate Green's function for the studied structure must be known to formulate MoM matrices: automatic incorporation of the radiation condition into the Green's function makes MoM particularly useful for radiation and scattering problems.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Even though the Green function can be derived in closed form for very simple cases, more complex structures necessitate numerical derivation of these functions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Full wave analysis of planarly-stratified structures in particular, such as microstrips or patch antennas, necessitate the derivation of Green's functions that are peculiar to these geometries.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] This can be achieved in two different methods.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] In the first method, known as spectral-domain approach, the inner products and convolution operation for MoM matrix entries are evaluated in the Fourier space with analytically-derived spectral-domain Green's functions through Parseval's theorem.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The other approach is based on the use of spatial-domain Green's functions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] This involves the inverse Hankel transform of the spectral-domain Green's function, which is defined on the Sommerfeld integration path.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Nevertheless, this integral cannot be evaluated analytically, and its numerical evaluation is often computationally expensive due to the oscillatory kernels and slowly-converging nature of the integral.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Common approaches for evaluating these integrals include tail extrapolation approaches such as weighted-averages method.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Other approaches include the approximation of the integral kernel.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] This method is known in the computational electromagnetics literature as the discrete complex image method (DCIM), since the Green's function is effectively approximated with a discrete number of image dipoles that are located within a complex distance from the origin.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The associated Green's functions are referred as closed-form Green's functions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] The method has also been extended for cylindrically-layered structures.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Rational-function fitting method, as well as its combinations with DCIM, can also be used to approximate closed-form Green's functions.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] Alternatively, the closed-form Green's function can be evaluated through method of steepest descent.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/method-of-moments-electromagnetics] For the periodic structures such as phased arrays and frequency selective surfaces, series acceleration methods such as Kummer's transformation and Ewald summation is often used to accelerate the computation of the periodic Green's function.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] A **perfectly matched layer** (**PML**) is an artificial absorbing layer for wave equations, commonly used to truncate computational regions in numerical methods to simulate problems with open boundaries, especially in the FDTD and FE methods.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] Berenger's original formulation is called a **split-field PML**, because it splits the electromagnetic fields into two unphysical fields in the PML region.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] A later formulation that has become more popular because of its simplicity and efficiency is called **uniaxial PML** or **UPML**, in which the PML is described as an artificial anisotropic absorbing material.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] This viewpoint allows PMLs to be derived for inhomogeneous media such as waveguides, as well as for other coordinate systems and wave equations.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] Specifically, for a PML designed to absorb waves propagating in the *x* direction, the following transformation is included in the wave equation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] where $\omega$ is the angular frequency and $\sigma$ is some function of *x*.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] where we have taken a planewave propagating in the +*x* direction (for $k>0$ ) and applied the transformation (analytic continuation) to complex coordinates: $x\to x+{\frac {i}{\omega }}\int ^{x}\sigma (x')dx'$ , or equivalently $dx\to dx(1+i\sigma /\omega )$ .
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] The same coordinate transformation causes waves to attenuate whenever their *x* dependence is in the form $e^{ikx}$ for some propagation constant *k*: this includes planewaves propagating at some angle with the *x* axis and also transverse modes of a waveguide.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] The above coordinate transformation can be left as-is in the transformed wave equations, or can be combined with the material description (e.g. the permittivity and permeability in Maxwell's equations) to form a UPML description.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] The coefficient σ/ω depends upon frequency—this is so the attenuation rate is proportional to *k*/ω, which is independent of frequency in a homogeneous material (not including material dispersion, e.g. for vacuum) because of the dispersion relation between ω and *k*.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] Perfectly matched layers, in their original form, only attenuate propagating waves; purely evanescent waves (exponentially decaying fields) oscillate in the PML but do not decay more quickly.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] PML is widely used and has become the absorbing boundary technique of choice in much of computational electromagnetism.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] Although it works well in most cases, there are a few important cases in which it breaks down, suffering from unavoidable reflections or even exponential growth.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] One caveat with perfectly matched layers is that they are only reflectionless for the *exact*, continuous wave equation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] Once the wave equation is discretized for simulation on a computer, some small numerical reflections appear (which vanish with increasing resolution).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] For this reason, the PML absorption coefficient σ is typically turned on gradually from zero (e.g. quadratically) over a short distance on the scale of the wavelength of the wave.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] In certain materials, there are "backward-wave" solutions in which group and phase velocity are opposite to one another.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] Fortunately, there is a simple solution in a left-handed medium (for which all waves are backwards): merely flip the sign of σ.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] A complication, however, is that physical left-handed materials are dispersive: they are only left-handed within a certain frequency range, and therefore the σ coefficient must be made frequency-dependent.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] Another important limitation of PML is that it requires that the medium be invariant in the direction orthogonal to the boundary, in order to support the analytic continuation of the solution to complex coordinates (the complex "coordinate stretching").
[src:computational-electromagnetics/perfectly-matched-layer] As a consequence, the PML approach is no longer valid (no longer reflectionless at infinite resolution) in the case of periodic media (e.g. photonic crystals or phononic crystals) or even simply a waveguide that enters the boundary at an oblique angle.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] The fundamental quantity that describes a field of radiation is called **spectral radiance** in radiometric terms (in other fields it is often called **specific intensity**).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] For a very small area element in the radiation field, there can be electromagnetic radiation passing in both senses in every spatial direction through it.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] where $\theta$ is the angle that the unit direction vector ${\hat {\mathbf {n} }}$ makes with a normal to the area element.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] The units of the spectral radiance are seen to be energy/time/area/solid angle/frequency.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] In MKS units this would be W·m−2·sr−1·Hz−1 (watts per square-metre-steradian-hertz).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] The equation of radiative transfer simply says that as a beam of radiation travels, it loses energy to absorption, gains energy by emission processes, and redistributes energy by scattering.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] Solutions to the equation of radiative transfer form an enormous body of work.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] The differences however, are essentially due to the various forms for the emission and absorption coefficients.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] A particularly useful simplification of the equation of radiative transfer occurs under the conditions of local thermodynamic equilibrium (LTE).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] Local equilibrium may apply only to a certain subset of particles in the system.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] For example, LTE is usually applied only to massive particles.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] In a radiating gas, the photons being emitted and absorbed by the gas do not need to be in a thermodynamic equilibrium with each other or with the massive particles of the gas in order for LTE to exist.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] In this situation, the absorbing/emitting medium consists of massive particles which are locally in equilibrium with each other, and therefore have a definable temperature (Zeroth Law of Thermodynamics).
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] The radiation field is not, however in equilibrium and is being entirely driven by the presence of the massive particles.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] where $B_{\nu }(T)$ is the black body spectral radiance at temperature T.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] Knowing the temperature profile and the density profile of the medium is sufficient to calculate a solution to the equation of radiative transfer.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] The Eddington approximation is distinct from the two-stream approximation.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] The two-stream approximation assumes that the intensity is constant with angle in the upward hemisphere, with a different constant value in the downward hemisphere.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] $I_{\nu }(\mu ,z)=a(z)+\mu b(z)$ where z is the normal direction to the slab-like medium.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] Note that expressing angular integrals in terms of $\mu$ simplifies things because $d\mu =-\sin \theta \,d\theta$ appears in the Jacobian of integrals in spherical coordinates.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] The Eddington approximation can be used to obtain the spectral radiance in a "plane-parallel" medium (one in which properties only vary in the perpendicular direction) with isotropic frequency-independent scattering.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] Thus the Eddington approximation is equivalent to setting ${\textstyle K_{\nu }={\frac {1}{3}}J_{\nu }}$ .
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] Higher order versions of the Eddington approximation also exist, and consist of more complicated linear relations of the intensity moments.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] This extra equation can be used as a closure relation for the truncated system of moments.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] Note that the first two moments have simple physical meanings. $J_{\nu }$ is the isotropic intensity at a point, and $H_{\nu }$ is the flux through that point in the z direction.
[src:computational-electromagnetics/radiative-transfer] This equation shows how the effective optical depth in scattering-dominated systems may be significantly different from that given by the scattering opacity if the absorptive opacity is small.
